If you thought posing in a bikini in the cold is as tough as the modelling industry gets, think again. US-based models shared with The New York Times some of the harrowing behind-the-scenes tales of the industry -- with objectification, racism and the lack of diversity at the top of the list. Here are our top 11 takeaways: Objectification "I had one guy who wanted my nipples to look hard for the shoot -- to show through. He literally just grabbed my nipple and was like see, we need it to be hard," Renee Peters. A post shared by Renee Peters (@model4greenliving) on Jun 2, 2017 at 10:21am PDT  "One of my first test shoots in New York – we drove out to the Hamptons and nobody told me that it was going to be topless. So I shot topless on the beach. The poses he was asking me to do...I have never felt so uncomfortable in my life," Grace Mahary. A post shared by Grace Mahary (@gracemahary) on Aug 16, 2017 at 10:06am PDT  "When I was young I shot with someone who went to jail for paedophilia...so that was really difficult to hear because he shot a lot of young women," Stella Duval. Mother of dragons A post shared by Stella Duval (@stelladuval) on Jul 23, 2017 at 8:15pm PDT  "They would talk about my body in front of me...they would say Julia is very wide, everyone keep that in mind, like in a meeting in front of people," Julia Geier.    Extreme youth "I was at a casting call...felt like everyone must've been 16, 17, 18 and here am I like past 25 –- really questioning am I still beautiful, do I still hold worth?" Renee Peters. A post shared by Renee Peters (@model4greenliving) on Sep 4, 2017 at 2:33pm PDT  "Other people would say that adolescent girls have sort of a prepubescent physique that is favoured by designers," Sara Ziff. A post shared by Sara Ziff (@saraziff) on Mar 3, 2017 at 8:50am PST  Diversity "There are about two spots in a show for black girls – out of maybe 50," Diandra Forrest. A post shared by Diandra Forrest (@diandraforrest) on Jul 29, 2017 at 4:48pm PDT  "We've also been sort of brainwashed that these Euro-centric Caucasian are what is attractive," Forrest. "There are things that I did to compromise my authenticity in order to get my foot in the door – just straightening my hair, changing what I wore," Ebonee Davis. A post shared by Ebonee Davis (@eboneedavis) on Aug 27, 2017 at 9:31am PDT  "My first agent here changed my name from Precious to Victoria," Precious Lee. A post shared by PRECIOUS LEE (@preciousleexoxo) on Jul 10, 2017 at 9:12pm PDT  "There's a petite category, a plus-sized category, but there isn't a category for people with disabilities." Jillian Mercado. A post shared by Jillian Mercado (@jilly_peppa) on Sep 1, 2017 at 10:31am PDT 